SIMPLE: name
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Name
<hw>Name</hw> <pr>(n⟦amac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>nama</ets>; akin to D. <ets>naam</ets>, OS. & OHG. <ets>namo</ets>,
G. <ets>name</ets>, Icel. <ets>nafn</ets>, for <ets>namn</ets>, Dan.
<ets>navn</ets>, Sw. <ets>namn</ets>, Goth. <ets>nam⟦omac⟧</ets>, L.
<ets>nomen</ets> (perh. influenced by <ets>noscere</ets>,
<ets>gnoscere</ets>, to learn to know), Gr. <grk>'o`mona</grk>, Scr.
<ets>n⟦amac⟧man</ets>. ⟦root⟧267. Cf. <er>Anonymous</er>,
<er>Ignominy</er>, <er>Misnomer</er>, <er>Nominal</er>,
<er>Noun</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The title by which any person or
thing is known or designated; a distinctive specific appellation,
whether of an individual or a class.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whatsoever Adam called every living creature, that was the
<qex>name</qex> thereof.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. ii. 19. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What's in a <qex>name</qex>? That which we call a rose⟦br⟧
By any other <qex>name</qex> would smell as sweet.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A descriptive or qualifying appellation given to a
person or thing, on account of a character or acts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>name</qex> shall be called Wonderful, Counsellor, The
mighty God, The everlasting Father, The Prince of Peace.</q>
<rj><qau>Is. ix. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Reputed character; reputation, good or bad;
estimation; fame; especially, illustrious character or fame; honorable
estimation; distinction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What men of <qex>name</qex> resort to him?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Far above . . . every <qex>name</qex> that is named, not only in
this world, but also in that which is to come.</q> <rj><qau>Eph. i.
21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will get me a <qex>name</qex> and honor in the kingdom.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Macc. iii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He hath brought up an evil <qex>name</qex> upon a virgin.</q>
<rj><qau>Deut. xxii. 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king's army . . . had left no good <qex>name</qex> behind.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Those of a certain name; a race; a family.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ministers of the republic, mortal enemies of his
<qex>name</qex>, came every day to pay their feigned civilities.</q>
<rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A person, an individual.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They list with women each degenerate <qex>name</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Christian name</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The name a
person receives at baptism, as distinguished from
<contr>surname</contr>; baptismal name; in western countries, it is also
called a <altname>first name</altname>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A given
name, whether received at baptism or not.</cd> -- <col><b>Given
name</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Given</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>In
name</b></col>, <cd>in profession, or by title only; not in reality;
<as>as, a friend <ex>in name</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>In the name
of</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>In behalf of; by the authority of.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧ I charge you <qex>in the duke's name</qex> to obey me.⟦rdquo⟧
<qau>Shak.</qau> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>In the represented or assumed
character of.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I'll to him again <qex>in name of</qex>
Brook.⟦rdquo⟧ <qau>Shak.</qau> -- <col><b>Name plate</b></col>, <cd>a
plate as of metal, glass, etc., having a name upon it, as a sign; a
doorplate.</cd> -- <col><b>Pen name</b></col>, <cd>a name assumed by an
author; a pseudonym or <altname>nom de plume</altname>.</cd> <au>Bayard
Taylor.</au> -- <col><b>Proper name</b></col> <fld>(Gram.)</fld>, <cd>a
name applied to a particular person, place, or thing.</cd> -- <col><b>To
call names</b></col>, <cd>to apply opprobrious epithets to; to call by
reproachful appellations.</cd> -- <col><b>To take a name in
vain</b></col>, <cd>to use a name lightly or profanely; to use a name in
making flippant or dishonest oaths.</cd> <au>Ex. xx. 7.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Appellation; title; designation; cognomen;
denomination; epithet.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Name</er>,
<er>Appellation</er>, <er>Title</er>, <er>Denomination</er>.
<xex>Name</xex> is generic, denoting that combination of sounds or
letters by which a person or thing is known and distinguished.
<xex>Appellation</xex>, although sometimes put for <xex>name</xex>
simply, denotes, more properly, a <xex>descriptive term</xex> (called
also <stype>agnomen</stype> or <stype>cognomen</stype>), used by way of
marking some individual peculiarity or characteristic; as, Charles the
<xex>Bold</xex>, Philip the <xex>Stammerer</xex>. A <xex>title</xex> is
a term employed to point out one's rank, office, etc.; as, the
<xex>Duke</xex> of Bedford, Paul the <xex>Apostle</xex>, etc.
<xex>Denomination</xex> is to particular bodies what
<xex>appellation</xex> is to individuals; thus, the church of Christ is
divided into different <xex>denominations</xex>, as Congregationalists,
Episcopalians, Presbyterians, etc.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Name</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Name
<hw>Name</hw> <pr>(n⟦amac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Named</conjf> <pr>(n⟦amac⟧md)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Naming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>namian</ets>.
See <er>Name</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To give a
distinctive name or appellation to; to entitle; to denominate; to style;
to call.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She <qex>named</qex> the child Ichabod.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam. iv.
21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus was the building left⟦br⟧
Ridiculous, and the work Confusion <qex>named</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mention by name; to utter or publish the name of;
to refer to by distinctive title; to mention.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>None <qex>named</qex> thee but to praise.</q>
<rj><qau>Halleck.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Old Yew, which graspest at the stones⟦br⟧
That <qex>name</qex> the underlying dead.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To designate by name or specifically for any
purpose; to nominate; to specify; to appoint; <as>as, to <ex>name</ex> a
day for the wedding; to <ex>name</ex> someone as
ambassador</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whom late you have <qex>named</qex> for consul.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(House of Commons)</fld> <def>To designate (a
member) by name, as the Speaker does by way of reprimand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To denominate; style; term; call; mention;
specify; designate; nominate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>named</ent>⟦br⟧
